{"key":"processedPost-12653447","value":{"id":12653447,"first":12652438,"last":12703282,"when":1275198144,"utime":"05/30/10 08:42 AM","content":"If it's really hot in summer, it's a good idea to change the soak water for fresh cold tap water half way through.&nbsp; We used to use the refrigerator to help prevent bacteria bloom during the soak, but as long as the soak water isn't too warm, that's not a problem.<br /><br />The consolidation phase allows the mycelium to consume some of the nutrients, storing them for the flush.&nbsp; If you fail to consolidate with brf cakes, they're so nutritious that you often get nothing but blobs of mutant tissue with no caps on first flush.&nbsp; This is because optimal nutrition levels for colonization are higher than for fruiting.&nbsp; It sounds counter-intuitive, but you actually want less nutrients in the fruiting stage.<br />RR","title":"Re: Old User, New Grow - Have some questions.","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}